It is possible, then, that the first part of Selimus proved to be a bad venture, and that Marlowe resolved to change his subject to one presenting similar aspects and capable of treatment on similar lines. In Tam- burlaine we find such a subject, and a treatment that is identical in all its features with that displayed in Selimus, even to the minutest bits of phrasing.
